<LegalPage title="Privacy policy" description="How CNVRT collects, uses, stores and protects personal information from website visitors, enquirers and business contacts.">
  <p class="legal-page__summary">This policy explains how CNVRT handles personal information when you visit this website, contact us, request an audit or discuss a potential project.</p>

  <h2>1. Who is responsible for your information</h2>
  <p>CNVRT is the controller of the personal information described in this policy. Questions, requests and complaints can be sent to <a href="mailto:hello@cnvrtdigital.co.uk">hello@cnvrtdigital.co.uk</a>.</p>

  <h2>2. Information we collect</h2>
  <p>Depending on how you interact with us, we may collect:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>your name, work email address and company;</li>
    <li>your website address and the page from which you submitted an enquiry;</li>
    <li>the service, project type, indicative budget, timing or audit area you select;</li>
    <li>the project brief, commercial goal or other information you choose to provide;</li>
    <li>correspondence, meeting notes, proposal history and the progress of an opportunity;</li>
    <li>technical and security information associated with a request, such as timestamps, browser information and a short-lived one-way identifier used to prevent abuse; and</li>
    <li>information from a company website or another public business source when you ask us to review it.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Please do not include sensitive personal information, passwords or confidential platform credentials in a public enquiry form.</p>

  <h2>3. How and why we use information</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Responding to enquiries and taking requested pre-contract steps.</strong> We use your details to understand the request, decide whether we can help, arrange discussions and prepare an audit, scope or proposal.</li>
    <li><strong>Operating our business and improving our response process.</strong> We maintain an enquiry history, internal notes, next actions and opportunity information where this is necessary for our legitimate interests in managing prospective work effectively.</li>
    <li><strong>Delivering agreed services.</strong> If you become a client, we use relevant information to perform the contract, communicate about delivery and manage the relationship.</li>
    <li><strong>Keeping required records.</strong> We retain invoices, agreements and related records where necessary to meet tax, accounting and other legal obligations.</li>
    <li><strong>Protecting the website and enquiry service.</strong> We use limited technical information to detect duplicate submissions, restrict abuse, investigate faults and maintain security. This is based on our legitimate interests in operating a secure service.</li>
    <li><strong>Analytics, advertising and optional marketing.</strong> Non-essential measurement or advertising technology will only be enabled where the required consent controls are in place. We will identify any separate marketing choice at the point it is offered.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Where we rely on legitimate interests, those interests are responding to genuine business enquiries, maintaining appropriate commercial records, improving our service and protecting our systems. We consider the information involved, its expected use and the effect on the individual before relying on this basis.</p>

  <h2>4. Who receives information</h2>
  <p>We do not sell personal information. We may disclose the minimum necessary information to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>hosting, database, authentication and form-processing providers, including Netlify and Supabase;</li>
    <li>professional advisers, insurers and carefully selected suppliers supporting our business;</li>
    <li>a purchaser or successor if the business or relevant assets are reorganised or transferred; and</li>
    <li>courts, regulators, law enforcement or another party where disclosure is required by law or necessary to establish, exercise or defend legal rights.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Providers acting for us may only use the information for the agreed service and must protect it appropriately.</p>

  <h2>5. International processing</h2>
  <p>Some technology providers or their subprocessors may process information outside the United Kingdom. Where this happens, we require an appropriate legal transfer mechanism, such as an adequacy regulation or approved contractual safeguards, together with relevant security measures. You can contact us for more information about the safeguards applying to your information.</p>

  <h2>6. How long we keep information</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Enquiries that do not become client work are normally retained for up to 24 months after the last meaningful contact.</li>
    <li>Client contracts, invoices and associated business records may be retained for up to six years after the relationship ends, or longer where law or an active dispute requires it.</li>
    <li>Internal enquiry notes follow the retention period of the relevant enquiry.</li>
    <li>Hashed rate-limit records used to protect forms are automatically removed after no more than 48 hours.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>We may delete information sooner when it is no longer needed. We review exceptions where a legal claim, safeguarding concern or regulatory requirement applies.</p>

  <h2>7. Security</h2>
  <p>We use access controls, authenticated administration, row-level database permissions, input validation and limited retention of security records. No online service can guarantee absolute security, but we take proportionate technical and organisational steps to reduce risk.</p>

  <h2>8. Your rights</h2>
  <p>Subject to the circumstances and exemptions in UK data protection law, you may have the right to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>request access to your personal information;</li>
    <li>ask us to correct inaccurate or incomplete information;</li>
    <li>ask for information to be erased or its use restricted;</li>
    <li>object to processing based on legitimate interests or to direct marketing;</li>
    <li>receive certain information in a portable format; and</li>
    <li>withdraw consent where processing relies on consent.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>To exercise a right, email <a href="mailto:hello@cnvrtdigital.co.uk">hello@cnvrtdigital.co.uk</a>. We may need to confirm your identity and will normally respond within one month.</p>

  <h2>9. Complaints</h2>
  <p>Please contact us first so we can try to resolve the issue. You also have the right to complain to the UK Information Commissioner’s Office. Information about making a complaint is available at <a href="https://ico.org.uk/make-a-complaint/" rel="noreferrer">ico.org.uk/make-a-complaint</a>.</p>

  <h2>10. Automated decisions and children</h2>
  <p>We do not use website enquiry information to make solely automated decisions with legal or similarly significant effects. Our services are directed at businesses and are not intended for children.</p>

  <h2>11. Changes to this policy</h2>
  <p>We will update this page when our forms, providers, analytics, retention practices or legal obligations change. The latest revision date appears at the top of the page.</p>
</LegalPage>
